</figure><h5><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/05/book-language-barrier-mandarin-english-holding-pattern/674105/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=books-briefing&amp;utm_content=20230526">My Novel Is a Love Letter My Mother Can’t Read</a></h5><p>“I worked on my debut novel, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/holding-pattern-jenny-xie/9780593539705?affiliate_id=atl-347&amp;utm_source=newsletter&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=books-briefing&amp;utm_content=20230526"><i>Holding Pattern</i></a>, in my off-hours. As its main characters, Marissa and Kathleen, collided on the page, their mother-daughter relationship unconsciously began to resemble my own. Their bond is strangled by the narratives they’ve internalized about each other and cleaved by cultural difference—though always resuscitated by love. But the book is in English, so my mom won’t be able to read it. I’ve essentially written a love letter that the recipient can’t decipher.”</p><p><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/05/book-language-barrier-mandarin-english-holding-pattern/674105/?utm_source=feed&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=books-briefing&amp;utm_content=20230526">Read the full article.</a></p><hr><p><small><em>When you buy a book using a link in this newsletter, we receive a commission. Thank you for supporting </em>The Atlantic<em>.</em></small></p>